voice_to_text: Over my shoulder. See? Mommy helps them sleep forever. Last night she was on the phone telling someone their dad wasn't suffering anymore. I checked our bank account on my phone and saw deposits I'd never noticed. Small cash amounts, twice weekly for months. Small enough that I wouldn't notice if I wasn't looking for them. Heidi, you said Mommy helped grandma, too. She nodded eagerly. Grandma was screaming from the hurt. Then Mommy gave her medicine from this bag, and she got quiet and peaceful. Mommy said it was a blessing. The garage door rumbled open. Brooks car pulled in. She walked into the kitchen to find me sitting at the table with the medical bag open in front of me. Her face went white. Ethan, I can explain. Heidi ran to hug her. Mommy, daddy found your helping medicine. Brooks eyes filled with tears. Heidi, go watch TV, please. After Heidi left, I stood up, my voice shaking. What the hell is this, Brooke? Are you stealing from the hospital? Are you selling them? She sat down slowly. Ethan, no. Tell me right now. These are controlled substances. This is morphine in our home. What are you doing with them? Brooke looked at me steadily. You're not going to let this go unless I explain everything, are you? Damn right I'm not. She took a breath. I'm giving terminal patients enough medication to end their lives peacefully. I steal these substances from the hospital and I give them To families whose loved ones are dying in agony. They take them home, administer them, and their family members die without pain. That's what I've been doing. I stared at her in shock. So you're kill when people. No. I'm ending their suffering when they're already dying. Brooke, this is. You could go to prison for the rest of your life. They could give you the death penalty. I'm giving these people the peaceful death they deserve. Brooke's voice rose. My mother begged me to end her. Ethan begged me, and I did it. I gave her enough morphine to stop her heart while she slept. You're insane, I said, backing away from her. You've lost your mind.

My daughter's homework asked, what does your mom do? She wrote, Mommy helps sick people sleep forever at the hospital. I was making Heidi's lunch when I found her homework worksheet crumpled in her backpack. The assignment had asked students to describe their parents jobs. In her messy second grade handwriting, Heidi had written word for word, my mommy helps sick people sleep forever at the hospital. I think the hospital doesn't know about it. I stared at the paper and how to chill up my spine because this sounded bad. But kids say the weirdest things, right? My wife, Brooke, deals with terminal patients everyday, helping families through their darkest moments. Heidi probably overheard Brooke talking about end of life care and got confused. But then Tuesday afternoon, my phone rang. Mr. Hale, this is Mrs. Alvarez, Heidi's teacher. We need to discuss Heidi's homework assignment about her mother's job. My stomach tightened. Is something wrong? I asked, and what I heard next sent me into shock. Heidi gave a presentation today. She told the class her mother brings medicine home from the hospital to help people sleep forever. She mentioned that families pay your wife privately for this service. She even said, your wife keeps a special bag hidden in your garage. I gripped the phone harder. Kids misunderstand things, Mr. Hale. Heidi described specific medications by name. Morphine, fentanyl. She even said her grandmother needed the special medicine before she went to heaven. The other parents are Concerned, I left work immediately, my mind spinning. How could Heidi even know those names? And what was this about Brooke bringing medicine home? When I got home, Heidi was coloring at the kitchen table. I sat beside her, keeping my voice gentle. Heidi, Honey, tell me about what you wrote about Mommy's job. She looked up with innocent eyes. I wrote what I see, daddy. Mommy helps people who are hurting really bad. That's right. She

They didn't pick up because they had turned their phones off to take the baby to some park for photos. I had to sit in the nurse's office for three hours until the school day ended and I could just walk home. When I got there, they were posting the pictures on Facebook, talking about their perfect little family. I was in the background of one photo walking in the front door looking like death and my mom cropped me out before posting it. That was kind of the moment I realized I was done expecting anything from them. Then last month, they sat me down again. My mom had this serious look on her face and I thought maybe something was wrong. Nope. They told me they've been trying for another baby for over a year and it's not happening. They're doing fertility treatments now. And here's the thing, they need me to watch Sophia every week during their appointments, not asking, telling. My mom handed me this printed list of instructions, like a full page, single spaced. It had Sophia's nap schedule, her snack preferences, what songs she likes, how to hold her bottle, everything. My dad said the appointments are two hours and they'd need me to do this every Thursday afternoon. I just stared at the paper. Then I looked at them and said no. My mom blinked. She goes, what do you mean no? I said, I mean, no, I'm not doing it. She's your Kid, you take care of her. My dad got this annoyed look and said it's only a few hours a week and I'm being dramatic. He actually said I owe them for everything they've done for me. I laughed. I couldn't help it. I asked him what exactly they've done. He didn't have an answer. My mom started tearing up saying I was being cruel and that family helps family. I told her we stopped being a family the second she called me a practice run. I said they made it clear I don't matter, so why would I help them make another kid they'll actually care about? My dad told me I was being selfish and immature. I grabbed my backpack and went to Jenna's house. I've been sleeping there for the past 3 days. Her mom didn't even ask questions. She just made up the guest bed and told me I could stay as long as I needed.

I told my parents I didn't have a kid. They did. And they need to take care of her, not me. My parents had me when they were 18 and 19, and honestly, they never let me forget it. Like, they didn't say it out loud at first, but you could just feel it. The way they'd sigh when I needed stuff for school. The way they never showed up to anything. Not one single volleyball game, not one art show. Nothing. I Learned pretty fast that if I needed something signed for school, I had to shove it in their face the morning it was due or it wasn't getting done. I'm 15 now, and I basically grew up at my friend's houses. My best friend Jenna's mom would pack me lunch sometimes because she knew my parents wouldn't. Another friend, Kyle, his dad taught me how to ride a bike when I was like, 10 because mine never bothered. It was embarrassing, but also kind of nice, you know? At least someone cared. My parents would celebrate their wedding anniversary every year with this huge dinner and flowers and the whole thing. But my birthday, maybe a card if I was lucky. Christmas was just whatever they'd get me. Socks or a gift card and call it a day. Meanwhile, they'd buy each other expensive watches and weekend trips. It was pretty clear where their priorities were. So two years ago, when they sat me down and told Me. They were having another baby. I was shocked. But then I was kind of hopeful. Maybe. Like, maybe they'd actually try this time. Maybe they'd Learned something. But then my mom started saying stuff, like how excited she was to finally be a real mom, how she couldn't wait to experience being a parent for the first time. And I'm sitting right there, right in front of them. Her friend called her out on it once. He was over for coffee, and my mom was going on about the baby, and her friend was like, um, you already have a kid. And my mom laughed and said I was the practice run, that this baby was the real deal. My dad nodded along like, that made total sense. I left the room, and nobody even noticed. When my sister was born, I completely disappeared. Like, I actually ceased to exist in that house. They named her Sophie, and suddenly it was all Sophia this, Sophia that. My mom quit her job to stay home with her. My dad started leaving work early on Fridays for family time. And by family, they meant the three of them. I got sick at school once. Like, really sick. Throwing up in the bathroom. The nurse called my parents five times. Five.

My fiance's best friend accidentally sent me a text meant for her. Did you tell him about Vegas yet? Lol. I responded, Vegas, tell me more. What she confessed next made me cancel the wedding during her bachelorette party. We've been together 4 years. Engaged one. The venue was locked. Caterer paid, dress fitted. She left Thursday for her bachelorette weekend. She and her bridesmaids. Laughter in the air, champagne flutes ready. Everything seemed perfect until Friday. Did you tell him about Vegas yet? Lol. I stared at my phone. Vegas. She went to Vegas 6 months ago for a work conference. Nothing ever about Vegas yet. But I played along. Vegas, tell me more. Three dots appeared. Stay, disappeared, stayed again. Then my phone rang. It was Jenna, her maid of honor. Her voice high, nervous. Tom, I meant to text Kayla. It's nothing. Just a joke about that conference. I said. We're getting married tomorrow. If there's something I should know about Vegas, now's the time. Silence. Can we meet? I can't do this over text. We met at a coffee shop downtown. Kayla had ducked out of party prep. Jenna sat, shaking face pale, tears in her eyes. The guilt's been eating me, she said. What happened in Vegas? She leaned forward. It wasn't just a conference extend. Kayla met up with her ex, Dimitri. They hooked up. Worse, they got married. My gut dropped. Married as in legal. Jenna showed me a photo. Kayla in a White dress, not a wedding gown. But in a small chapel, standing beside Dimitri, they were married. Legal, Jenna stammered. We were drunk, thought it was a joke, but it was legal. She tried to get it annulled quietly. She said it would be handled before your wedding. So she wanted me to marry a woman who's already married. She told me she would finalize it after your wedding. She wanted you to believe the paperwork was done so no one would know. I barely heard her. My mission was set. I left the coffee shop. I drove to the Ritz where the bachelorette party was going full swing. Laughter, music, champagne. I knocked. Tori, Kayla's sister, answered, glass in hand. Tips. Tom, you can't be here. Boys aren't allowed. I squared my shoulders. We need to talk now. Kayla appeared behind her in a sash and tiara. Her face drained. What are you doing here? I said, Vegas, Dimitri, the chat.

Am I the a hole for calling the police immediately when my sister's family broke into my new house with a stolen spare key? I, twenty seven f, have spent my entire life playing second fiddle to my sister Anna. 30th. She's always been the golden child. Growing up, Anna got princess parties with ponies. I got frozen pizza and a cake from Walmart. She got new toys, I got knock offs with pieces missing. Her college fully funded mine. I had to pay rent to live at home while working a $9 per hour job and studying computer science. Every time I asked why she got help and I didn't. You're independent. You'll figure it out. So I did. I skipped meals, borrowed textbooks, and still graduated with a 3.9 GPA. No Celebration, just another night at home like nothing happened. Meanwhile, Anna graduated with a 3.2 and got a catered party with a DJ and champagne toasts. I stopped sharing my life with them. Especially when I started house hunting. I knew the second they found out, they'd find a way to make it about Anna. And they did. A coworker accidentally let it slip that I was looking. Within days, my mom called all fake cheerful. Kate, we've been looking at houses for you. You'll need at least four bedrooms for the kids when they visit, and maybe a pool. I don't have kids. They meant Anna's kids. Then the link started. Every day. Giant Homes with five bedrooms, yards, extra rooms for Josh's office or space for mom and dad to visit. Anna even sent me one that said this would finally give us room to breathe. Us. I stopped responding, silenced the group chat, finished closing on a house by myself. A quiet two bedroom cottage outside the city. It wasn't big, but it was mine. Kitchen, cozy porch, garden in the back. I didn't tell them a thing. Then came the family dinner. I showed up, sat through fake small talk, knowing something was coming. Sure enough, after the lasagna, mom pulled out her phone like she was announcing a real estate deal. We found the perfect place. Five bedrooms? Yes! Sweet. And it's only a few blocks from Anna's. I set my fork down and said, I already bought a house. Silence. Anna stared at me. Wait, what? A two bedroom? Where are we supposed to stay? You're not. Boom! Mom lost it. How could you make such a huge decision without us? We've been helping you. No, I said you've been house shopping for Anna, not for me.

My daughter saved for eight months to buy a bike. Then her piggy bank was suddenly empty. I went to grab some quarters from my daughter's piggy bank for parking and found nothing but three pennies rolling around inside. Layla was only seven and had been saving up for months to buy a new bike with all her birthday and tooth fairy money. The piggy bank felt way too light when I picked it up, and those three pennies made this sad little noise when I shook it. When Layla got home from school, I sat her down at the kitchen table with her favourite snack. Sweetie, where did all your piggy bank money go? She kept her eyes on her shoes and mumbled something I couldn't hear. What was that, honey? I asked gently. I gave it all to Aubrey, she finally said louder. She never has lunch money, and yesterday the lunch lady didn't let her eat. My heart swelled with pride, but I was also confused. Why didn't this kid have lunch money? The next morning, I gave Layla five extra dollars. Give this to Aubrey for lunch today, okay? She jumped up and threw her arms around me. Thanks, Mommy. You're the best, she said, before running to catch the bus. I couldn't stop thinking about why some kid didn't have lunch money every single day. Because as even when money was tight, we always figured it out. Around lunchtime, my phone rang. This is Principal Rouse, could you come in for a meeting about Layla? Twenty minutes later, I was sitting in the principal's office. Your daughter has been giving money to another student, which is technically against school policy, but we need to talk about the whole situation here. I braced myself. Aubrey's family has been going through a lot. We can't share all the details, but your daughter has been making sure that child eats lunch every day. She paused and looked at me carefully. The family applied for free lunch, but there's a waiting period and tons of paper.

voice_to_text: Have you ever been recruited to be Santa's helper at a mall by a desperate elf? Last December I was killing time at the mall, waiting for my girlfriend to finish her shift at the jewelry store, when a tiny woman in an elf costume grabbed my arm. Please, please, you have to help me, she whispered, her fake pointed ears drooping. Santa just quit mid shift and there are 40 kids in line. I'm 6 foot 4 with a beard I've been growing since October. She looked at me like I was the answer to her prayers. I don't know anything about being Santa, I protested. She was already dragging me toward the North Pole set up. Can you say ho ho, ho and not swear in front of children? When I nodded, she said, you're hired. Before I could object, she shoved me into a break room where a red suit hung on a chair, still warm from the previous Santa. He left because kid threw up on him, she explained, tossing me the pants. Third time this week. I should have run, but she looked so desperate, and somewhere outside, children were waiting. The suit was too small, the jacket barely closed, the pants ended at my calves, and the beard kept sliding sideways. The elf, who introduced herself as Brenda, looked me over and sighed. It'll have to do. Just remember, every kid gets a candy cane. No promises about specific gifts. Absolutely no holding babies. My First kid was easy, a shy five year old who whispered she wanted a Dinosaur. I deepened my voice, said something about checking my list, and sent her off with a candy cane. I thought I had this figured out. Then came Tyler. Tyler was seven, skeptical, and armed with questions. Why does your beard smell like coffee? He demanded. How do you fit down chimneys if you're so fat? Before I could answer, he pulled my beard down and announced to the entire line, this isn't the real Santa! Panic spread through the crowd. Parents glared, children started crying. Brenda

I declined. Long silence. You have property that belongs to her. Don't think we won't get it back. Send me a list. I'll have my lawyer review it. Days later, her brother Julian showed up at my office. You've got her engagement ring. Mom wants it back today. The ring was conditional upon marriage. The condition is no longer being met. That ring's worth more than your car. We can make this unpleasant. Are you threatening me? I asked calmly. Phone recording in plain sight. Give back the ring, give Isabel her furniture half and apologize publicly. No. The ring's in secure storage. She can have furniture if she pays moving costs. And I won't apologize for being dumped by a text. That evening, I drove to storage with a sickening feeling. My grandfather's desk had a secret. The compartment I'd shown Isabelle. Once. I opened it empty. My grandfather's watch. Gone. She'd stolen it before I'd even started packing. The one thing truly irreplaceable to me. I'd mistaken my calm for weakness. Fine. They'd get a war fought. With receipts and documentation, I filed small claims for the stolen watch, camera, laptop and Isabel's share of final rent. Court day arrived. I wore a simple suit with one organized folder. They arrived as a phalanx. Marcus, Eleanor, Isabel and Julian. I presented simply. Here's the list. Bills, receipts, photo of me wearing my grandfather's watch. And the text that started it all. I read it aloud. I'm not marrying A broke man. Either upgrade or I'm gone. Marcus argued the items were gifts. Text was hyperbole. I was vindictive. The judge looked at Isabel. Did you take the watch from the desk? Her eyes flickered to her mother. It was a gift. Is that true, sir? No, your honor. It was my grandfather's. Priceless to me. She ruled in my favor on all counts. They were ordered to return everything and pay the watches value plus outstanding rent. Julian had to physically restrain Marcus from yelling at the judge. A week later, a courier delivered the camera, laptop, and a check. Oh, note, I sold the ring and used it as down payment on a condo. A real upgrade. Months later, Isabel texted at 2 a m. Heard you bought a condo. Guess my little push worked. You should thank me. I deleted it without replying.

I was mistreated my whole life because of my special sister. She now tried walking down the aisle at my wedding, and I finally got payback. Growing up, my sister Brianna was the golden child. And I mean golden. When I was 7, I saved up birthday money for months to buy this doll I wanted. The day I brought it home, Brianna threw a tantrum saying she wanted it. My parents made me give it to her because she's more sensitive and needs extra love. I cried for hours. They grounded me for making Brianna feel bad with my crying. At 13, I got straight A's for the first time. My parents took me and Brianna to celebrate at the restaurant Brianna picked with the cake flavor Brianna liked, even though I hate chocolate. When I asked why my achievement party was all about her, my dad said I was being selfish and ungrateful. Brianna smirked at me the whole dinner. At 16, I worked after school for eight months and if $2,000 for a used car. My parents found my savings envelope hidden in my closet and took it. They use my money to pay for Brianna's driving lessons and insurance because she needed a car more than me since she had anxiety about taking the bus. When I begged for it back, they said, family helps family. I didn't get a single dollar back. Brianna got her license in a car while I took the bus for Two more years. Every single time Brianna came first, I stopped expecting anything different. Fast forward 10 years. I'm engaged to the most amazing guy, Logan. I didn't want Brianna in the wedding at all, but my parents called me, crying. If Brianna isn't the maid of honor, we're not coming. We'll tell the whole family you excluded your sister on purpose. I caved because I didn't want the drama. Biggest mistake of my life. During rehearsal, Brianna started her comments. White isn't really your color. You'd look better in cream or maybe blush. This song's too slow for the bridesmaids. It'll drag and bore people. Oh, and I've been thinking. I should walk down the aisle, too, right before you. It would look so elegant having both sisters make an entrance. People will love it. I shut her down hard. No changes. This is my wedding, not yours. She pouted, but I thought that was the end of it. Wedding day arrives. I'm in the bridal suite getting ready when my coordinator rushes in, panic. Your sister brought a white dress. Like, wedding white. She says it's cream, but it's white white. I told her to handle it and just keep Rihanna away from me until the ceremony. The ceremony starts. My bridesmaids walk down perfectly. Then suddenly, the music changes. Not my chosen song. I look up, confused, and Brianna standing at the back of the aisle in that white dress, holding a bouquet I definitely didn't give Her posing

What's a lesson you had to learn the hard way? When I was broke in college, my roommate's cousin Kevin offered me what seemed like the easiest job ever. Manage an online clothing store's Instagram. Post pictures, reply to comments, copy paste stuff. 300 bucks a week, cash through Zell every Friday, plus he'd give me a free iPad to use. I didn't even have to leave my dorm room. I said yes in, like, two seconds. The store was called Sunset Styles. Kevin sent me a drop box full of pictures. Crop tops, jeans, sneakers, dresses. All I had to do was post them with captions he wrote, schedule them for certain times, and answer DMs. Simple stuff. The first week, I got paid exactly on time. I remember buying groceries without checking my account first. Felt amazing. Then the messages started coming in. At first, just one or two people asking where their orders were. I'd forward the messages to Kevin like he told me. He'd say he'd handle it. But more kept coming. People were getting mad. One girl said she ordered a hoodie three weeks ago and got nothing. Another said the tracking number didn't work. I started feeling weird about it, but Kevin kept saying the shipping company messed up and he'd fix everything. By week three, my DMs were full of angry people. I'm talking hundreds of messages. People calling me a scammer, saying I stole their money. I tried talking to Kevin, but He just kept saying, forward it all to him and don't worry about it. He even gave me a script to copy paste. So sorry for the delay. Shipping is backed up, but your order is coming soon. I used that message probably 500 times, and this girl named Becca made a TikTok. She ordered a jacket for 60 bucks and never got it. But here's the thing. My face was in the Instagram stories. Kevin had me do a few try on videos to make the page look real. So Becca Screen recorded my videos and put them in her TikTok with text saying, this girl scammed me and won't respond. That video got a million views in two days. Suddenly, my Instagram was flooded. People found my personal account. They found my school. Someone posted a screenshot of me in the campus library with the caption, scammer goes here. My roommate came back one day and asked if I was actually stealing people's money. I tried explaining it wasn't me, but she looked at me like I was lying. I texted Kevin freaking out. I said I wanted to quit. He said I couldn't just quit because people were.

In this slow princess wave to the guests, stopping to smile at people. She's literally trying to have a bridal moment at my wedding. Some guests look confused. Others are whispering. But here's what none of them knew. Logan's groomsmen were my cousins. The same cousins who watched me get screwed over my entire childhood. The same ones who knew every single story of Brianna. I getting whatever she wanted while I got nothing. As Brianna reaches the halfway point, still waving and smiling, my cousin Dan and his brother set directly into the aisle in perfect sync. They pick her up horizontally like a surfboard. One guy has her shoulders, one has her legs. Brianna starts screaming, what are you doing? Put me down right now! They don't say a word. They just carry her straight past the shocked guests, out the side door and into the parking lot. Her bouquet falls on the ground. The entire church goes dead silent, and someone in the back starts clapping. Then more people join in. Then everyone's clapping and laughing. My parents jump up to chase after her, but my Aunt Helen physically blocks the exit. She's a big woman, and she plants herself there like a wall. She looks at them and says, sit down. You've ruined enough of her life. You're going to sit here and watch her get married. We finished the ceremony. It was perfect. Beautiful. Everything I wanted. During cocktail hour, I found out Brianna spent The entire reception, sitting in her car, crying because Dan stood guard at the door and told her if she tried to come back in, he'd call actual security to have her removed from property. My parents tried to apologize at the reception. I walked away mid sentence. They sent emails, texts, called Logan's parents to intervene and mediate. I blocked them and ignored everything for months. Six months later, they finally wrote a real apology letter, admitting they bailed me for decades and destroyed our relationship. They asked if we could start over and rebuild. I responded, maybe when you actually treat both your daughters equally. Until then, I'm done. Brianna never apologized. Last I heard, she's still telling people I humiliated her on purpose at my wedding. Good. She humiliated me for 25 years. Turn about is fair play.

You cared that much, you'd give up your seat and go sit with him in the back. But you want to keep your upgraded seat and have your kid up here? That's not my problem. That's when she lost it. Like, full on started wailing. Not crying, wailing. She's going, how could you do this to a child over and over again? People are staring. The flight attendant comes over, looking stressed. A woman sobbing now, telling the flight attendant I'm refusing to let her son sit with her. The flight attendant looks at me, and I just show her both boarding passes and explain I paid extra and offered to switch if she reimbursed me or moved to her own son's seat. The flight attendant's face changes. She tells the woman, ma'am, you can either take your assigned seat or switch with the passenger seated next to your son. We need to close the doors. The woman grabs her bag and storms off toward the back, still crying and muttering about how cruel people are these days. Like, two minutes later, this guy in his 20s sits down next to me, huge grin on his face. Dude, thank you so much. That kid would not stop kicking my seat during boarding, and his mom just kept saying, boys will be boys. Literally giddy about getting bumped up to Economy Plus for free. I thought it was over, but then my boyfriend text me after I land saying I was Too harsh. Apparently his mom thinks I should have just been nice and switched, because that's what good people do. And that I probably made that woman feel like a terrible mother.

And I mean golden. When I was 7, I saved up birthday money for months to buy this doll I wanted. The day I brought it home, Brianna threw a tantrum saying she wanted it. My parents made me give it to her because she's more sensitive and needs extra love. I cried for hours. They grounded me for making Brianna feel bad with my crying. I look up, confused, and Brianna is standing at the back of the aisle in that white dress, holding a bouquet. I definitely didn't Give her posing like she's the bride. My parents are in the front row smiling and filming like this was. And all along, my mom's literally crying happy tears. I'm frozen at the altar. Logan squeezes my hand and whispers, we've got this. Brianna starts.

I made a seat swapper cry. So I'm boarding this flight to visit my boyfriend's family for the first time. I saved up for three months to get an economy plus seat because I'm tall and regular economy makes my knees feel like they're gonna snap off. I get to my seat 12 A, throw my bag up top, and I'm literally just sitting down when this woman taps my shoulder. She's got this fake sweet smile on and goes, hi, would you mind switching seats with me? My son has really bad anxiety and he needs to sit with me. I look at her boarding pass. 32B. That's literally in the back of the plane, middle seat next to the bathroom. I paid an extra $70 for the seat. I'm like, oh, I actually paid for the seat, but I can switch if you reimburse me the $70 I spent on it. Her face goes red immediately. Are you seriously going to make a nine year old with anxiety sit alone? What kind of person are you? I'm confused now because, like, if her kid has such bad anxiety, why didn't she buy seats together? So I asked, wait, where are you sitting? 12C. She says, that's literally two seats over from me, also economy plus. So why don't you just trade seats with whoever sitting next to your son? Then you can sit with him. She crosses her arms. I need the leg room. I have back problems. I almost laughed. So you need the leg room, but your son with anxiety can just deal with sitting alone in the back. She starts getting loud. You're being incredibly selfish right now. He's a child, and you're his

I don't understand all these food restrictions nowadays. Finally, I just said, look, I have a medical condition. I can't eat gluten or I get really sick. I'm not being picky. I literally cannot digest it. His mom laughed and said, honey, that's just being a picky eater with extra steps. My generation didn't have all these made up allergies. I was so done at that point. I excused myself to the kitchen to start cleaning up, even though we weren't finished eating. When I came back 10 minutes later, they had eaten everything. Like everything. All the leftover chicken, all the potatoes, even the green beans, which they were complaining about earlier. My husband's plate was empty too. I just stood there staring at the empty dishes. I had barely eaten anything because I was so stressed from their comments. His mom notices me looking and goes, well, I guess it wasn't that bad after all. We were just hungry. Then she laughs like it's some big joke. I looked at my husband and he just shrugged, like literally just shrugged. Didn't say anything to defend me or acknowledge that this was messed up. So I grabbed my phone and ordered Thai food just for me. I got pad Thai, spring rolls, mango, sticky rice, the works, and like 40 bucks. When the delivery guy showed up, his parents were still there having coffee and cake that his mom brought. I answered the door, got my food and sat Down at the kitchen counter to eat it. His mom comes in and goes, what's all this? We just had dinner. I said, yeah, well, I didn't get to eat the dinner I spent three I was making because you guys finished it all while calling me a picky eater. I'm eating food that I can actually enjoy without being insulted. She got all huffy and said I was being dramatic. His dad tried to smooth things over by saying they didn't realise I hadn't eaten much. But his mom kept going, we didn't eat that much. And besides, if you made enough food, there would have been plenty for everyone. I just stared at her while eating my pad Thai. Then I said, you're right. Next time I'll make sure to cook enough food to feed people who complain about it the entire time and then eat all of it anyway. His mom's face went bright red and she started saying something about respect and how I was being rude in my own home. My husband finally spoke up and said, maybe we should all just calm down. His parents left pretty quickly after that.

My brother's wedding. I was handed a paper badge that read, limited access guest. My mom whispered, that means no plate. I looked over, walked to the gift table, retrieved my envelope with a 7,500 dollar fun check, and said, I think you won't need this anymore. Then I left. My brother ran after me, and my parents shouted, come back! The envelope sat there on the gift table, plain white, bent at the corner. Inside was a 7,500 dollar check I'd saved for months. Extra shifts, vacations, saying no to things I wanted. All of it. I told Ryan weeks earlier I had something big planned. He'd called me late one night, voice tight, saying, Mel, I don't know how we're going to afford the honeymoon. I said, don't worry, I've got you. At the reception, check in. The woman handed me a paper badge. Not gold trimmed like everyone else's, just white, flimsy, printed in thick black. Limited access guest. My mom appeared beside me. That means no plate, she whispered, then walked off before I could respond. I checked the seating chart. My name wasn't listed. Not at the family table, not anywhere. I wasn't a guest. I was a placeholder they forgot to remove. I'd driven two hours to get here, bought a new dress, taken the day off work. All of it for nothing. I stood near the wall, watching Ryan toast, watching my parents clap, watching everyone settle in. My aunt was laughing at Something someone said. My cousins were taking selfies at their table. They saw me. They just didn't care. So I walked back to the gift table, opened my envelope, pulled out the check, and said, loud enough, I think you won't need this anymore. Chairs scraped. Someone shouted my name. Ryan's voice, then my parents, both yelling, come back! Come back! I didn't. I drove home and didn't sleep. Not from anger, but because I kept seeing that paper badge in my hands. By morning, the text started. Can we talk? Please don't make this a thing. No apologies, just deflection. My mom wrote, we assumed you'd be okay with standing, since you always say you don't care about fancy stuff. My dad called. I ignored him. Then he texted, come over, we want to talk. Your brother's here, too. I went, not to fix anything, just to watch them squirm. They were all in the living room when I arrived. My dad said it was unfortunate how things went. My mom used the word oversight three times. Ryan barely spoke. When he did, he said, I didn't know it would be like that. I thought you'd understand. I let them finish. Then I said I might change my mind.

Room shifted instantly. My mom sat up, eyes wide. My dad exhaled relief. Ryan finally looked at me. My mom started talking fast about how the money would go to the honeymoon, how she didn't want this little thing to hang over us. My dad chimed in about families getting through rough moments. I stood. I need time to think. I left them with that word, my buzzing in their ears. For once, they wanted something from me. Three days later, my mom called. They were delaying the honeymoon. No check, no trip. That's when I remembered. I'd loaned them my second car six months ago. It was still in my name, still on my insurance. They'd said it was temporary, a week or two while theirs was in the shop. That was in March. It was now September. I scheduled a tow for Friday morning. 9 12 a m, my phone rang. My mom, there's someone outside towing the car. Did you do this? Yes. I said, silence. Why? I'm changing insurance companies. She said they needed the car. I said, then maybe you should rent one. That's what I'd have to do, right? This is about the wedding, isn't it? No. I said, this is about patterns. I hung up. That afternoon, a text from someone I didn't know. This is Kiara's cousin. I helped organize the wedding. You were originally listed as family. Full access, seated with your parents and Ryan. Three days before the wedding, your Mom changed it. She emailed a revised list. Ryan approved it. I remember thinking it felt wrong, but I figured it was a family thing. They knew Ryan saw my name on the original list and let them move me. They wanted the envelope, not me. I deleted the family group chat, blocked my parents, muted Ryan's number. Two days later, my dad tried again. Family is complicated. We all make mistakes. We love you. No apology, just excuses. I didn't reply. I opened the file labeled loan terms and deleted it. A week later, Ryan's fiance texted. I don't know what happened, but I still think you did the right thing. I replied, thank you. Two months later, Ryan sent one message. I miss you. I read it. Then I blocked his number. They didn't lose a daughter. They lost access to my generosity.

Sorry to interrupt. I just have something everyone should hear. Before the wedding, I connected my phone to the Bluetooth speaker. Thank you. Saved password and hit play. Rebecca's voice filled the yard. He's sweet, but boring. Once we get the house sold, we can finally be together for real. Silence, then gasps. A glass shattered. Rebecca's face drained. That's not what it sounds like. Oh, it's exactly what it sounds like. I held up printed photos. Her and Bradley at the Marriott. Her mom's hand went to her mouth. You've been sleeping with your lawyer and plotting to sell my house. Proof, time stamps, audio, everything. Rebecca screamed. You hired someone to follow me? That's illegal. Recording a fraud scheme. Totally legal. Her sister Nicole muttered, Becca, what the hell? Rebecca snapped, shut up! Tom's loaded. He can afford it. That house is half mine anyway. Eight months, I said. You've lived there eight months, paid zero rent, contributed nothing. You don't own a brick. I pulled out an envelope. You've been served eviction notice. Got 30 days to get out. Your things are already packed. Dennis and Mike are loading the truck right now. Storage unit on Riverside. First month's on me. She lunged at me. Her mom and sister had to grab her. You can't do this. We're engaged. Not anymore. I said calmly. Weddings canceled. Venue vendors all notified an hour ago. And Bradley's wife? She got copies of everything. That shut her up. Her mom, Started crying. Guests gathered. Someone yelled, holy shit! As I walked out. By the time I got home, Rebecca's ring was on the dresser. The PI texted, Bradley's wife just called his office. He's finished. I poured a drink, opened my blinds, and watched the movers haul her boxes away. That's how I ended an engagement, exposed two frauds, and kept my house. All in one afternoon.

Letters, thinking I'd be homeless. Those nights flooded back. Crying alone at 2 a m. The shame of thinking I'd messed up. The fear of calling my parents to admit I was failing. And you knew. I continued. You watched me fall apart and told me they were mistakes. You promised you'd handle it. Kira blew on her nails, looking bored. I was going to fix it eventually. Eventually, I screamed. I'm getting kicked out in three days. She rolled her eyes. You're being dramatic. Just ask your parents for money. That's when I noticed the gold bracelet on her wrist. Delicate and expensive. My rent money turned into jewelry. I called the landlord right there. I'm filing a police report, I said. Kira stole my rent payments. I have Venmo proof. My landlord's voice turned serious. Come to my office tomorrow morning with your records. Bring your roommate. Kira jumped up, knocking over the Polish bottle. Pink liquid spread across the carpet. You're seriously calling the cops? You stole $2,550 from me and almost destroyed my future, I said coldly. What did you expect? The next morning, we sat in my landlord's office. Kira's parents were on speaker phone. Her mother was crying. She'll pay everything back. Her father said. Please don't call the police. My landlord wouldn't back down. Your daughter committed theft and almost cost my tenant her education. I'm ending her lease immediately. She has 48 hours to leave. Kira was crying, mascara running down her Face in black streaks, but I felt nothing except cold relief. She lost her apartment that week, but I kept her designer bags. I never spoke to her again.

I drove home 15 over the limit. When I opened the door, Kira was on the couch painting her toenails bright pink. A green face mask covered her face, and cucumber slices sat on a plate beside her. We need to talk right now, I said. She didn't look up. Can it wait? This polish takes forever to dry, the landlord said. I'm three months behind on rent, she said. You pay your part on time, but I've been sending you $850 every month. Kira's hand froze. Pink polish dripped onto the carpet. Oh my god, I totally forgot to forward it, she said casually, still focused on her toes. I've been so busy with my Instagram. I'll send it right now. Forgot for three months? My voice cracked. That's $2,550. I'm getting kicked out Friday, losing my scholarship and having to quit school. She sighed. Like I was being annoying. It's not that serious. I had expenses come up. I was going to pay it back eventually. That's when I saw the shopping bags behind the couch. Three bags with designer logos from stores I'd never entered. What expenses? Those bags. Your Miami trip last month. Kira shrugged and went back to her nails. I needed a mental health break. College is stressful. My hands clenched into fists. I've been eating ramen for every meal. I skipped my best friend's birthday because I couldn't afford it. I had panic attacks over those letters, thinking I'd be homeless those nights. Flooded back crying. Alone at 2 a m. The shame of thinking I'd messed up. The fear of calling my parents to admit I was failing. And you knew. I continued. You watched me fall apart and told me they were mistakes. You promised you'd handle it. Kira blew on her nails, looking bored.

How do you know that? She blinked. Oh, you mentioned it. No, I didn't. I hired a private investigator the next morning. Three days later, he called. You might want to sit down. Bradley isn't just her lawyer friend. They've been meeting at hotels twice a week for four months. He sent photos, Marriott, his car, his apartment. Dates going back to before the prenup talk. Then the kicker. Bradley's deep in debt. Specializes in partition sales, forcing co owners to sell property. Their plan was simple. She gets on my deed, they force a sale, split the profit. My fiance and her side piece lawyer were trying to steal my house. Her bridal shower was in two weeks. 40 guests, mom hosting. I smiled for the first time in days. I played perfect. Fiance attended tastings, smiled for photos, even met Bradley for paperwork. He reeked of Cologne and arrogance. No rush, buddy, he said, smirking. Sooner's better for tax purposes. Sure, pal. The PI kept sending proof. Audio this time. Rebecca laughing in Bradley's car. He's sweet, but boring. Once we sell the house, we can finally be together for real. That was my green light. Bridal shower, day two PM. Packed backyard. Champagne and gold decorations everywhere. Rebecca and a tiara opening gifts. Mom answered the door. Tom, what are you doing here? It's bad luck. Need a quick word with the bride. I walked straight to the center of the party. Every woman turned. Sorry to Interrupt. I just have something everyone should hear before the wedding. I connected my phone to the Bluetooth speaker. Thank you. Saved password and hit play. Rebecca's voice filled the yard. He's sweet, but boring. Once we get the house sold, we can finally be together for real. Silence, then gasps. A glass shattered Rebecca's face.

My landlord found me at a coffee shop and said, you're three months behind on rent. I have to start eviction by Friday if you don't pay the $2,550 you owe. I froze because that made no sense. Kind. I pay every month. My scholarship required stable housing within five miles of campus, which meant eviction would cost me my financial aid and force me to drop out completely. I pulled out my phone with shaking hands. Look. $850 on the first of every month. September, October, November. My landlord squinted at my screen. Why are you sending money to Kira? You both pay me separately. I looked at him all confused. Kira said it would be easier if I sent her my half and she'd bundle both payments together. He shook his head. I never agreed to that. Kira pays her part on time every month. But I haven't gotten a dollar from you since August. My heart rate went up, and it wasn't because of the caffeine. I'd worked two jobs to never miss a payment for this room. The eviction letters, I whispered. Kira said they were billing mistakes. She told me she'd handle it. My landlord shook his head. Those definitely weren't mistakes. No payment by Friday means I have to file eviction papers. Three months times $850. I had pocketed $2,550 and never sent a cent to the landlord. My coffee spilled as I stood up, but I didn't care. I drove home 15 over The limit. When I opened the door, Kira was on the couch painting her toenails bright pink. voice_to_text: At dinner I said, can't wait for the family reunion. My brother laughed. You're not invited. It's for real family. Everyone laughed. I just smiled and left. Four days later, my dad tried to withdraw 20 four hundred dollars. I sent a screenshot. Payment denied. Must be that family only policy. Two days later, I heard a loud knock on my door. I've been the one who found the cabin, confirmed dates and sent the deposit. Weeks went by. Group chat went quiet. I asked twice if we were still going. Nobody answered. That night at dinner, everyone acted normal. Halfway through, I brought it up, so when's the reunion happening? But he looked me straight in the eye. You're not invited. It's for real family. The table erupted full on shoulders, moving laughter. Lana smiled and looked down. Mom kept chewing. Dad snorted. I smiled too, not because it was funny, but because I finally understood who they were. I stood up, folded my napkin and walked out. Four days later, dad tried pulling $2,400 from the joint emergency account I'd opened three years ago when Mom's hospital bills started piling up. The withdrawal was declined. I was the only one contributing. They used it for car repairs, Lana's textbooks, Cody's rent. Never said thank you. Two days later, heavy pounding on my door at 8:00am. Through the people, dad, mom and Cody. I opened the door just wide enough. What is this about freezing the account? I kept My voice calm. The accounts in my name. I put the money in. You weren't entitled to it. It's family money. That's not what I heard at dinner. You actually took that seriously. It was a joke. Nobody corrected you. You all laughed then stayed silent when I left. Get over yourself. You can get over the canceled vacation. Mom's face paled. Canceled. Charged back the deposit. I booked it. I paid for it. It's gone. Dad, explode. I made every call, paid the down payment, did all the work while you plan to cut me out. I turned to mom. Remember your emergency dental work last year? I covered that. Quietly, she nodded slowly. The hospital co pays the car insurance, your medications, all me. Dad, panic flashed across his face. And mom. The credit card you opened in my name three years ago, I paid it off, but not the.

Two Sundays ago, during a family dinner, my mother in law started going on and on about how my parenting was too soft and how I was raising my son to be weak. Then she pulled out a little candy bar with peanuts and almost handed it over to my son before I slapped it out of her hand. I stood up and glared at her. That's it! You're never going to see your grandson until you figure out how to actually be nice and respect my family's boundaries, I said sternly, taking my son to his room to make sure he's fine. My husband went up after a couple of minutes with an angry expression. You shouldn't have done that to her. Now she's downstairs crying when all she wanted to do was help. Help? You're kidding, right? She tried harming our child. Your son! I shouted back. He shook his head at me and walked back out to continue having dinner with his family. After that, I stopped inviting his family over, declined every time she offered to babysit. My husband was still angry at me, saying I was being unfair and holding a grudge over nothing. But I didn't care. My son's health was my priority. But last week I had to leave town when my mom suddenly collapsed. My husband promised he'd stay home with our son, so before I left, I showed him exactly where to find the Epipen and reminded him about all our Rules. Absolutely no peanuts. Okay, I got it. Go and focus on your mom, he said just before I had to rush out. But apparently, after an hour of watching our kid, my husband needed to urgently step out to visit some friends and watch an important game. He dropped off our child to his mom, handed over the Epipen, and told her all the rules that she called useless just weeks ago, expecting her to follow it. She rolled her eyes and said, fine, fine. And he thought that was the end of it. But he was wrong. After he left, she decided to prove once and for all that I've been lying about the allergy. She gave my son peanut butter cookies, thinking she could finally show everyone I was being overdramatic. But then she watched his face swell up and panicked as he started turning purple and blue right in front of her. She called my husband, crying for help while she struggled with the Epipen. He quickly called 9 1 1 and raced back to see the damage. My husband called me an hour later at the hospital. Our son. He had an attack. I drove like a maniac to get there just in time to hear his mother confess that she'd given him peanut butter to see if the allergy was real. But she wasn't even sorry. If you hadn't cuddled him so much, maybe his immune system would be stronger. Even the staff couldn't Believe it. That's when I decided that my mother in law needed to be unalived. My brother demanded I sell him Mom's house for cheap. But mom had been playing a game none of us knew about. My older brother, Vince started visiting our mother at the nursing home every Sunday. After his third visit, something was off. Mom started grabbing her purse whenever I walked in. She'd ask the nurses to count her jewelry. After I left, she flinched when I tried to hug her. I was lost. For 20 years, I've been the one paying her bills, driving her to appointments, making sure she had everything she needed. Vince hadn't visited once in five years. Until suddenly, he was there every week. Mom had dementia and was getting more confused. One afternoon, a nurse pulled me aside. She told me mom kept asking I was really stealing from her. I felt sick. That's when I knew Vince was feeding her lies about me. Two weeks later, mom died, still believing I was a thief. I've been living there for three years, keep it maintained. Then he hit me with his offer. $200,000. The house was worth 800,000 easy. He called it generous, considering what I'd stolen. From mom? I told him no. His voice changed. He said, fine. I'll make sure everyone knows what you did. Your boss, your neighbors, everyone in town will know you robbed our sick mother. It just said, Vince has been stealing from me. I know what he's going to do. Trust me. There was a key taped to the paper. That was it. The lawyer said mom told him to only give this to me after Vince claimed the house. I had no idea what any of it meant. The key looked like a bank key, but I couldn't be sure. She'd been protecting my sister while I bullied her, while I mocked her. So I tell her I'm sorry.

I bullied the teacher's pet for two years. Then she saved my family. My ex best friend and I had been inseparable since third grade, when she protected me from a bigger kid trying to bully me. But then we grew up, and by junior year, everything changed. She became the teacher's pet. Always staying after class, defending teachers, first to volunteer for everything. The rest of us couldn't stand it, but there she was, practically living in the main office. Always carrying this fancy silver pen she never let anyone touch her. Brother gave it to her. She said teachers loved her. Students, not so much. Especially me. She stopped sitting with us at lunch. Started eating alone in the library. Senior year, I started the group chat. Called it Zoe's Fan Club. With a vomit emoji. Posted screenshots every time she volunteered for something. Drew a cartoon of her kissing the principal's butt. She tried talking to me once. Cornered me by my locker, hands shaking. Please just trust me, she whispered. I laughed in her face, told her we were done. The hurt in her eyes should have stopped me. My little sister, Lillian, started freshman year that fall. Within weeks, something was wrong. She'd come home crying about pop quizzes she swore never happened. Teachers marking her absent when she was there, her grades tanking despite studying every night. I blamed Lillian. You need to try harder, I kept saying while she sobbed at the kitchen. Table able. One day, Zoe left a note in my locker. Check on Lillian, please. I ripped it up. Teacher Appreciation Week arrived in May. Zoe insisted on planning everything. She organized breakfast, decorated the lounge, created a whole assembly program. The day of the assembly, I sat in the back, ready to mock her speech. The principal walked to the microphone, beaming at Zoe, even encouraging us to stand up and cheer for her. Zoe is a shining example of what dedication looks like. We hope all students can strive to be as amazing as her. Zoe walked to the podium carrying a folder and the silver pen she always has with her. She told me once it was a special pen her brother gave her. I didn't even know she had a brother. I have something to share, she said quietly. My heart stopped. I don't know how to explain it, but her voice.

My mom was robbed and beaten half to death by three teenage boys. They had no idea my dad killed people for a living. This happened back in my hometown in Iran, when I was 14 years old. My mom was one of the few women in our village with an actual job, and on this particular night, she was working late. Dad only got home at 3:00am, still covered in dried blood from his shift earlier. And when he saw mom wasn't home, he instantly grabbed his keys. The eldest son, I, went with him. And after what, hours of driving, we found her. My mother was lying in a bush, her hijab half torn, purple bruising around her body and in between her legs. She'd been laying there for hours, too injured to get up, and without a phone to call for help. She was somehow alive, and my dad instantly scooped her up. We could have taken her to the hospital, but my dad worked for the government and knew that doctors would look at an assaulted woman and claim she was asking for. So instead, he treated her at home, using what he Learned from his job to heal all the broken bones and injuries she had. He handmade her crutches out of wood he got from nearby trees. He helped her regain the confidence to go outside. He took over the cooking and cleaning, despite it being against our hometown law. Within five months, my Mother was back to full health. My dad originally had no plans of revenge. Whoever did this would be impossible to track back down. Until the day it happened again. Two full years after the first incident, my mother was walking home from the market in broad daylight when she was surrounded by three boys from the nearby village. They've been eyeing her for weeks. When she tried to walk by them, they formed a tight circle around her and started closing in. First, they took her hijab, ripping it off her and tearing it into pieces. When my mother tried to protest, the oldest slapped her across the face. She fell into the sand. And once she was on the ground, things got worse. They dragged her by force into an alleyway where nobody could see or hear her scream and did things to her I don't want to describe. She only made it home because another woman found her in that alleyway and recognized her. When the front door opened and I saw my mom on this woman's shoulders, struggling to breathe, I felt the worst case of deja vu. Throughout the next couple of months, I saw a different side of dad. He was the tender, loving, and caring husband he'd always been. But when he thought nobody was watching, I saw this rage in his eyes I'd never seen. My son said I was ruining his life by obsessing over grades. He regretted it when I stopped checking them entirely. My son Geo stormed through the front door last Monday, slamming it so hard the pictures shook. He threw his backpack against the wall and glared at me. You're the worst mom in the entire junior class! He shouted, his face red with anger. I was sitting at the kitchen table reviewing his SAT prep schedule I'd carefully planned out. Every other mom trust their kid. Louis's mom never checks his grades. Eddie's mom doesn't force him to study on weekends. Sarah's mom says she doesn't believe in college. He was practically shaking. Now you treat me like I'm 5 years old. I can't breathe without you asking about homework or college essays or AP score. I tried to explain that junior year determines college options. That's all you care about! He yelled, my GPA, not me! Eddie's mom told him, CS are fine. You freak out over 1 B+! My chest tightened hearing this. I only stressed so much because I wanted him to succeed. Fine, I said, quietly closing my laptop. From now on, your grades are your responsibility. That night, I lay awake thinking about my own past. I'd grown up, or watched my single mom work three jobs just to rent. I'd studied by candlelight when the power got cut off. I watched my mom starve herself so she could feed me. Got into state School on scholarships I fought for. Now I made decent money. The nurse and Geo would never know that struggle, but maybe I was projecting my fears onto him. The next morning I deleted the app to check his grades from my phone. When Geo mentioned he had a calculus test, I just nodded and kept making breakfast. He looked confused but pleased. By Wednesday he was playing video games instead of studying. I didn't say anything. Friday came and he skipped his SAT prep class to hang out with Eddie and Lewis. I bit my tongue and said nothing. The next week he started coming home later saying he was at study groups. I didn't question it even though.

After I dropped my kid off at school, his teacher cornered me and asked, why is your son absent today? No, he's not. I just watched him walk inside. Mrs. Stevenson's face went pale. Well, he didn't make it to my classroom. She looked at her attendance records. In fact, Theo hasn't made it to my classroom at all for the past three weeks. My stomach dropped. That's impossible, I stammered out. I've been dropping him off every morning and staying until I personally see him go in. Missus Stevenson hesitated, then picked up her classroom phone. I think you need to speak with Principal Miles right now. We walked through the hallway in silence. Other teachers kept glancing at us and looking away quickly. The principal's secretary was already crying when we arrived, like she knew something. Principal Miles had security footage pulled up on his computer. Come look at this. The screen showed the front entrance. There was Theo scanning his ID badge at 7:00am, walking toward the classroom with his Dinosaur backpack. The timestamp read October 24th This morning. Mister Davis, watch what happens next. Camera angle switched to the main hallway. I could see Theo in the morning crowd of kids. He walked toward his classroom hallway, then suddenly veered left toward the gym. The time stamp showed 7:48 a m. Another camera angle. The gym hallway. Theo pushed through the emergency exit door. A man in a hard hat and construction vest was waiting. Theo climbed Into a white pickup truck, they drove away. The time stamp, 7:49 a m. That's been happening every morning for three weeks. Miles. His voice was shaking. We presume this was authorized. The man said he was Theo's uncle, picking him up for family medical appointments. He showed me a folder. Dozens of permission slips with my forged signature. I've been trying to call you, but the number on file was disconnected. That's when Mrs. Stevenson interrupted. Mr. Davis, there's something else. CPS is coming to your house today at eleven a m. They received a report about educational neglect. If Theo isn't there, if we can't prove where he's been, you could. In custody. My hands were shaking as I pulled out Theo's phone from my pocket. He'd forgotten it in the car. The screen lit up with notifications. 47 unread messages, all from Uncle Mike. My blood went cold. Uncle Mike was Theo's stepdad's uncle. I opened the messages. Don't tell your dad. You know what happens if you tell. The last message sent this morning at 7:30 a m. If you don't come today, you'll never see your mom.

And she broke into this genuine smile. She took the rose and laughed, saying she couldn't remember the last time someone had given her flowers. Joel pulled me aside and whispered, dude, what are you doing? I didn't understand the question. I was just being a decent date. Dinner started with Joel trying to dominate the conversation, but Sam kept asking me questions, genuinely interested. She found out I was into classic movies, and suddenly we were deep in conversation while Joel and Jean faded into the background. After dinner, Sam suggested bowling the alley. Sam and I destroyed Joel and Jean. We were laughing, high fiving, and she kept playfully trash talking me every time I got a gutterball. Then Sam wanted ice cream, so we walked to her favorite local shop. She ordered this weird combination of flavors, and I tried it. Even though it sounded terrible, it was actually amazing. We sat on a bench outside just talking while Joel and Jean wandered around nearby. I wasn't trying to steal anyone's spotlight. I was literally just talking to Sam and laughing at her jokes. Jean seemed perfectly happy watching her friend enjoy herself. When we said our goodbye eyes, Sam hugged me and whispered, thank you for actually trying tonight. She asked if I wanted to hang out again sometime, just us. I said yes before I could overthink it. The second Sam and Jean left, Joel absolutely unloaded on me in the parking lot. He said, Bringing a rose was cringe and that I'd embarrassed him, that I dressed way too formally. I looked down at my flannel and jeans completely confused. Then he said the quiet part out loud. You were supposed to entertain Sam so Jean would focus on me, not actually impress her. You made me look bad. I just stared at him. Made him look bad. I barely spoke to Jean the entire night. She had every opportunity to give him attention, but she chose to watch her friend be happy instead. Joel said if I was going to act like that, I should have just stayed home. I got in my car and left without responding. Now he's sending me paragraph long texts about how I violated bro code and ruined his chances with Jean, all because I got a haircut and bought a rose.

My friend is mad at me for dressing nice for a double date. I've known Joel for five years now, and we've always been total opposites. He's the confident, athletic type who turns heads when he walks into a room. Me, I'm the chubby, quiet guy who's been losing his hair since 23. We're friends, but we exist in completely different worlds when it comes to dating. So when Joel asked me to be his wingman on a double date, I was surprised. He'd finally gotten somewhere with Jean, this girl he'd been chasing for weeks. Catch gene wanted to bring her friend Sam along. Sam was apparently new to dating and nervous, so gene thought a double date would feel safer. Joel made it very clear what my role was. Keep Sam entertained so he could focus on Jean. Simple enough. I agreed because I had nothing better to do on a Saturday night. Now, here's the thing about Sam. We'd crossed paths a few times at university before this. Every single time, she seemed completely unimpressed by me. And I don't blame her. Those encounters happened when I was wearing the same three rotation outfits. Old band shirts, stretched out hoodies, and jeans that had seen better days. I looked exactly like what I was. A guy who'd given up on trying. But this time, I figured I should at least make an effort. Not for any romantic reason, just basic respect. If someone's giving up their Saturday Evening to sit across from me, the least I could do is not look like I just rolled out of bed. So yesterday I went to an actual barber. I had them cut my hair as short as possible without fully shaving it. Trying to own the ball holding rather than hide it. I cleaned up my beard and shaped it properly. Then I hit the mall and bought clothes that actually fit. A white button up, a flannel to layer over it, and dark jeans. Nothing expensive, just presentable. The day of the date, I kept second guessing everything. Was the flannel too much? Eventually, I grabbed a single rose from the grocery store on the way. Corny, maybe, but I thought it might break the ice. I ended up running five minutes late. My phone was loading with text from Joel. When I finally walked up holding that rose, the energy shifted completely. Joel's face fell immediately. Jean's eyebrow shot up in surprise, but Sam, her entire face transformed. Her eyes actually sparkled.

This mom is adjusting to her new normal after losing her hands and legs because of all things, a dog Lick. Marie Trainer woke up from a 10 day coma to find her limbs had been amputated. She cried the hardest I ever cried in my life. The life changing tragedy had its origins during a vacation in the Caribbean with her husband. Marie says she was using her key card to access her hotel when she accidentally nicked herself on her wrist. It was a tiny little scratch, a silly accident. It hardly hurt. Four days later, Marie got very sick and was rushed to the hospital with a severe infection and septic shock. Her arms were turning black all the way up just below her shoulders. It turns out that her dog's saliva carried a bacteria called capnocytophaga. It's quite common in dogs, but what happened to Marie is a very rare occurrence. Her husband Matthew is doing his best to lift her spirits. I love her to death. She's everything to me.

He met a 16 year old on a dating website, invites her to his home, makes her feel comfortable. His domestic partner is also there. Everything is fine. And then suddenly a piece of jewelry went missing and they allegedly blamed the 16 year old. That is when the two of them tortured this girl for at least 4 days, ending her life with a billiard ball down her throat over jewelry. His name is Steven Grass. He is 35. And she is Michelle Brandis. She's 37. And most importantly, this is Miranda Corset. Miranda had been on a dating website. When she met Steve, they started talking and he invited her over to the house. Everything went fine that first day and she goes back home. She had been living with her grandmother because both of her parents have passed away and she also has an 11 month old baby. So the following day she decides to go back over to their home and she never came home. And unfortunately, because she has frequently just left and not came back, the grandma didn't report it because she assumed she just went off again, which is honestly so awful in itself. So she then goes back. She's at their home. That's when the jewelry goes missing. That's when they torture her. That's when they take her life. And then the two of them dismember her and throw her in a freaking trash can. Right now the police believe that her Body is in a landfill because of her history. This is not taken seriously. I don't understand how anyone could do this to anyone for literally any reason. As of now, they are charged and they are sitting in a jail cell. And I hope Miranda receives justice. And I am begging every teenager, learn from her mistake that she did not get the chance to learn from.

voice_to_text: Breaking news, a crazy plan was proposed to clean the statue of Liberty through this bizarre method for America's 250th. But officials warned that it'd actually be a terrible idea. Thirty years after the statue arrived in America, a devastating fire at a nearby military ammunition depot caused a massive blast that severely damaged its interior, preventing any future public access to the torch. That same year, the statue turned fully green as its original copper brown finished oxidizing deferred it. Now, less than a year before the nation's 250th anniversary, some are calling for a major restoration of the statue by first using lasers to grip the green layer, exposing the original copper brown underneath, and then completely reworking the upper internal structure to reopen access to the torch. But government officials say this would be one of the dumbest ways to waste taxpayer money as not only would the copper simply reoxidize after less than 10 years, it would also cause irreparable damage to Lady Liberty as the green layer is actually preventing the statue from corroding. voice_to_text: A local woman takes on Walmart in court and wins. Leslie Nurse says she was at the self checkout at the Sims Walmart with her husband and three kids, fighting a malfunctioning scanner, even getting help from a Walmart associate. After she thought she'd finished and paid, she was stopped by an asset Protection manager. She was eventually charged with stealing $48 worth of groceries. She was eventually arrested, mug shot taken, but the criminal charge was eventually dropped when no one from Walmart showed up to court. By then, she said, the damage to her reputation had already been done, her ability to make a living stifled by the criminal charge. What was worse, she continued to receive demand letters from a Walmart affiliated law firm offering to drop the matter if she paid them $200, but it turns out many people do. During testimony in the lawsuit she filed against the company, an expert testified Walmart routinely uses to add insult to injury, Walmart never produced a video that would have been recorded at the self checkout area that would have proved nurse shoplifted or didn't. At the end of this lawsuit, filed in 2018 and delayed by the COVID pandemic, a unanimous jury found for nurse and awarded her $2.1 million in punitive damages.

voice_to_text: Oh, my god. Oh, my god. A 12 year old boy struck his mother in the head with a baseball bat just because she stopped him from playing on his phone. After doing this, the boy took the phone from his unconscious mother's hand and continued playing. His mother, Amanda Miller, lay on the floor for four hours after being struck in the head. During that time, her son, Liam Miller, did not call for help or alert anyone and just kept playing on his phone. It wasn't until Liam's father came home from work that he found Amanda lying on the floor. He rushed her to the hospital where doctors found that Amanda had severe brain hemorrhaging and had been unconscious for too long. While they managed to save her life, the prolonged brain bleeding meant Amanda was at high risk of becoming a vegetable. Liam, however, told his father that his mother's injuries were due to her accidentally falling while he was asleep and unaware of what had happened. What Liam didn't know was that his father had installed surveillance cameras in the living room to protect his wife and kids. The cameras caught the shocking scene. Liam's father immediately called the police and officers arrested Liam. According to the police, Liam had repeatedly asked for his father's forgiveness but was denied. Liam was charged with first degree murder and assault, but his father did not attend the court hearing and did not offer forgiveness since Liam was Only 12, he didn't meet the legal standards for adult sentencing. The judge ultimately sentenced Liam to five years in prison with one year of probation, do you think the verdict was fair?

voice_to_text: Police department throughout the region say they are seeing more and more drivers trying to find ways to actually hide their license plate tags from those red light camera lenses. Obscuring license plates on purpose is nothing new, but two things are increasingly making that practice a real issue for law enforcement. No. 1, as you mentioned, the proliferation of red light cameras as we have here in the Boulevard. And No. 2, high tech methods being used to keep police from seeing those tags. This may seem like something out of a British spy novel, but it's a real device found on a vehicle that was recently impounded by Philadelphia police. And while remote controlled license plate flippers are not common, people driving around with obscured or fraudulent and tags is. If you drive around, notice there's paper tags everywhere and many of them aren't legitimate. They can be copied on a copier or printed out off the computer. Captain John Ryan, commanding officer of the Major Crimes Unit says there's no way of knowing for sure if the implementation of red light cameras resulted in more people obscuring their tags, but those cameras sure are capturing images of a lot of them.

I took it and saw a phone number written on the back. Looking up at her fading figure, pure joy rushed through me. Two people drawn to each other, falling in love came naturally. We soon got married. Months ago, doctors told me I had a malignant brain tumor. There was nothing they could do. I tried to tell her so many times, but I couldn't. I knew her too well. Watching her teach our son, I smiled. Such a warm, beautiful moment. But the longer I watched, the more it hurt. I hid in the bathroom, wiping away my tears. The plan I prepared for so long echoed in my head, and I finally decided to go through with it.

voice_to_text: A local woman takes on Walmart in court and wins. Leslie Nurse says she was at the self checkout at the Sims Walmart with her husband and three kids fighting a malfunctioning scanner, even getting help from a Walmart associate. After she thought she'd finished and paid, she was stopped by an asset Protection manager. She was eventually charged with stealing $48 worth of groceries. She was eventually arrested, mugshot taken, but the criminal charge was eventually dropped when no one from Walmart showed up to court. By then, she said the damage to her reputation had already been done, her ability to make a living stifled by the criminal charge. What was worse, she continued to receive leave demand letters from a Walmart affiliated law firm offering to drop the matter if she paid them $200. But it turns out many people do. During testimony in the lawsuit she filed against the company, an expert testified Walmart routinely uses. To add insult to injury, Walmart never produced a video that would have been recorded at the self checkout area that would have proved nurse shoplifted or didn't. At the end of this lawsuit, a unanimous jury found for nurse and awarded her $2.1 million in punitive damages.
